# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: level-editor-design
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:level-editor-design/game-development-tool] A **game development tool** is a specialized software application that assists or facilitates the making of a video game.
[src:level-editor-design/game-development-tool] Some tasks handled by tools include the conversion of assets (such as 3D models, textures, etc.) into formats required by the game, level editing and script compilation.
[src:level-editor-design/game-development-tool] Almost all game development tools are developed by the developer custom for one game, or by a console manufacturer (such as Nintendo or Sony) as part of a game development kit.
[src:level-editor-design/game-development-tool] Though tools may be re-used for later games, they almost always start out as a resource for a single game.
[src:level-editor-design/game-development-tool] While many COTS packages are used in the production of games—such as 3D packages like Maya and 3D Studio Max, graphic editors like Photoshop and IDEs like Microsoft Visual Studio—they are not considered solely game development tools since they have uses beyond game development.
[src:level-editor-design/game-development-tool] The game tools may or may not be released along with the final game, depending on what the tool is used for.
[src:level-editor-design/game-development-tool] For contemporary games, it is common to include at least level editors with games that require them.
[src:level-editor-design/game-development-tool] Early in the history of the video game industry, game programming tools were non-existent.
[src:level-editor-design/game-development-tool] This wasn't a hindrance for the types of games that could be created at the time, however.
[src:level-editor-design/game-development-tool] While today a game like *Pac-Man* would most likely have levels generated with a level editor, in the industry's infancy, such levels were hard coded into the game's source code.
[src:level-editor-design/game-development-tool] Images of the player's character were also hard-coded, being drawn, frame by frame, by source code commands.
[src:level-editor-design/game-development-tool] As soon as the more technologically advanced use of sprites became common, game development tools began to emerge, custom programmed by the programmer.
[src:level-editor-design/game-development-tool] Today, game development tools are still often programmed by members of the game development team by programmers, often whose sole job is to develop and maintain tools.
[src:level-editor-design/game-development-tool] Numerous tools can be used to assist in game development.
[src:level-editor-design/game-development-tool] Often developers use tools to convert 3D model formats and graphic image formats into custom formats (though, increasingly, importers and exporters handle these tasks).
[src:level-editor-design/game-development-tool] Level editors are used to create environments and other tools may be used to view assets before they are incorporated in the game.
[src:level-editor-design/game-development-tool] For a contemporary commercial game, a half dozen tools or more may be used to assist in the game creation process.
[src:level-editor-design/game-development-tool] Game tools change very often during the development process.
[src:level-editor-design/game-development-tool] The look and facility of a tool from the beginning of a project to the end may change dramatically.
[src:level-editor-design/game-development-tool] Often features are added with very little testing to assist other developers as fast as possible.
[src:level-editor-design/game-development-tool] The use of a tool also changes so much that users may have difficulty operating it from one day to the next as late-added features change how it is to be used.
[src:level-editor-design/game-development-tool] Since facility is often the primary goal for tools, they may be very user-unfriendly, with little or no built-in help.
[src:level-editor-design/game-development-tool] For tools that are to be shipped with the game, often debugging and user-friendly features are done near the end of the development process.
[src:level-editor-design/game-development-tool] Outside of the game development team during the game's creation, many tools would have little facility.
[src:level-editor-design/game-development-tool] Level editors, however, once entirely proprietary, have increasingly been included with the shipping game to allow users to create their own game scenarios.
[src:level-editor-design/game-development-tool] Some games, such as Firaxis' *Civilization IV*, are built with user modification in mind and include numerous tools for game customizing.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] In video games, a **level** (also referred to as a **map**, **mission**, **stage**, **course**, **zone**, **area**, or **round**, depending on context) is any space available to the player during the course of completion of an objective.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Video game levels generally have progressively increasing difficulty to appeal to players with different skill levels.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Each level may present new concepts and challenges to keep a player's interest high to play for a long time.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] In games with linear progression, levels can represent areas of a larger world, such as Green Hill Zone from the *Sonic the Hedgehog* series.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Games may also feature interconnected levels, representing locations.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Although the challenge in a game is often to defeat some sort of character, levels are sometimes designed with a movement challenge, such as a jumping puzzle, a form of obstacle course.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Players must judge the distance between platforms or ledges and safely jump between them to reach the next area.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] These puzzles can slow the momentum down for players of fast action games; the first *Half-Life*'s penultimate chapter, "Interloper", featured multiple moving platforms high in the air with enemies firing at the player from all sides.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] In the early days of video games (1970s–2000s), a single programmer would develop the maps and layouts for a game, and a discipline or profession dedicated solely to level design did not exist.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Early games often featured a level system of ascending difficulty as opposed to progression of storyline.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] An example of the former approach is the arcade shoot 'em up game *Space Invaders* (1978), where each level looks the same, repeating endlessly until the player loses all their lives.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] 1983's *Lode Runner* was one of the first titles to ship with a level editor.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Its designer, Doug Smith, reputedly paid neighborhood children to design levels for the game.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] The same year, the multiplayer dungeon crawl *Dandy* was released, and it also shipped with a level editor which was documented in the manual.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] *ZZT* (1991) is a later game with user-accessible mapping and scripting.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] A game genre that required significant amounts of time to design areas were text-based games, such as MUDs.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Often, promoted users were assigned to make new paths, new rooms, new equipment, and new actions, often using the game interface itself.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] 3D first-person shooters *Doom* (1993) and *Doom II* (1994) were two of the first games to attract focused game modding activity, and many WAD level files were made for them.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] One of the reasons was a clear separation between the level files and game engine itself.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] *Half-Life*, *Quake 3*, and many other games have notable mapping tools and communities focusing on user-generated content.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Level design for each individual level in a modern game typically starts with concept art, sketches, renderings, and physical models.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Once completed, these concepts transform into extensive documentation, environment modeling, and the placing of game specific entities (actors), usually with the aid of a level editor.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] A level editor may be distributed as a complete stand-alone package, at times, rivaling commercial 3D modelling software.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] There are various steps involved in laying out a map and these steps may vary dramatically across the many different game genres that exist as of the 2020s.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Cut scenes may be triggered by events in a level, but require distinctly different skills, and may be produced by a different person or team.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] The level design process may be iterated several times before achieving the desired outcome.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Level designers and concept artists may also be required to provide a pre-rendered map of the level (or entire game world) for the player.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Level design is necessary for two primary purposes: providing players with a goal and providing players with enjoyable play experience.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Good level design strives to produce quality gameplay, provide an immersive experience, and sometimes, especially in story-based games, to advance the storyline.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Levels are generally constructed with flow control in mind; that is, directing the player towards the goal of the level and preventing confusion and idling.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] This can be accomplished by various means.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Often the level layouts feature power-ups and items positioned so that collecting them inevitably makes the player move in the correct direction.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] This is one of the basic player direction techniques and is most often seen in platformers.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Lighting and illumination, as well as distinctly-coloured objects, are often used to unambiguously guide the player towards the correct path.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Similarly, clearly marked choke-points can be introduced.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Yellow paint is often used in modern games to guide the player in the right direction, though this approach is commonly criticised due to its unsubtlety.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Another method is strategic placement of obstacles and aesthetic environment props that direct the player's attention to "clear" paths instead.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] This is often used in closed, "stuffed" environments.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Levels may be designed to force the players to explore the map and advance.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Most Real-Time Strategy maps give each player a starting base, but will have resource distribution and terrain features designed to draw players out of their base and engage each other.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Teamplay maps can provide noticeable advantages to one team over another, when designed poorly.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Commonly on older hardware, most games would load a single level and all of its assets at one time, and when the player completed the level, the next level would be loaded.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] The player would be presented with a loading screen while the game loaded level information from storage.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] This can effectively make the transition from one level to another level appear to be seamless and avoid the use of loading screens.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] This is known as level streaming or in-game streaming, and is often used for open world games to give the perception of a fully-interconnected space.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] There are often tricks used to give the computer hardware sufficient time to load the assets for the next area.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] The player's speed may be reduced, while story cues are presented to draw the player's attention.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] The player may be required to enter areas in which their view of the world is plausibly restricted, sometimes referred to as "loading tunnels".
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] With newer consoles, such as the PlayStation 5 and Xbox Series X and Series S, special SSD arrays alongside software libraries that have a total high data throughput can eliminate the need for any loading tunnels in a seamless world game.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] A level designer is a game designer who makes environments and scenarios using a level editor and other tools.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Level designers will usually work on a level from pre-production to completion – working with both incomplete and complete versions of the game.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Video game programmers usually produce level editors and design tools for the designers to use.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] This eliminates the need for designers to access or modify game code.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] As opposed to the level editing tools sometimes available to the community, level designers often work with placeholders and prototypes aiming for level consistency and clear layout before required artwork is produced by game artists.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Many level designers have skills as both a visual artist and game designer, although in recent years the responsibility for visual-, structural- and gameplay-related tasks has been increasingly divided among several specialists.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] A wide variety of tools may be used by someone designing and making a level.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Although it is faster to design models and textures with general-purpose multimedia development tools, games usually require the data to be in a unique format suited for that game's engine.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] For this, specific compilers and converters of models, textures, and audio data may be required to lay out a level.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Sometimes, professional 3D editing software, such as 3D Studio Max, Blender, AutoCAD, Lightwave, Maya, Softimage XSI or Grome is used, usually customized with a special plugin developed for the specific game.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] A **level editor** (also known as a **map**, **campaign** or **scenario editor**) is a game development tool used to design levels, maps, campaigns and virtual worlds for a video game.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] An individual involved with the development of game levels is a level designer or mapper.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] In some cases, the developer of a video game includes built-in level editing tools; for example, a track editor for a racing game.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Other times they may release an official level editor for the game as a separate application.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Sometimes players of the game develop fan-made level editors.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Developing level editors will allow the game creator to use the same load- and rendering routines as the game itself, and may make it easier and more pleasant to create levels.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Developers of FOSS-games may argue that a game is not complete until other users easily can add new levels.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] One of the first 3D games which became popular partially due to level editors and fan-made maps, other game addons, and other works related to the game, was *Doom*.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] The development of various third-party editors led to the formation of an online community trading fan-made maps.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] A level editor is often limited to designing levels for only a certain game engine.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Developing a level editor takes a lot of time; it is more time- and cost-efficient to release multiple games using the same engine instead of developing a new engine and level editor for each game.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] As level editors generally allow for limited game-development work, to make larger changes to a game than simply adding new levels, a software development kit (SDK) is sometimes needed.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] In the early years of video gaming, some games came with a utility called a "construction set".
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] This was similar in many ways to a level editor.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Some games used them to make extra levels, whereas others (like the *Shoot-'Em-Up Construction Kit*) used them as a means to develop a game rather than be a game in itself.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Maps' design can significantly impact the gameplay.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] For example, the gameplay may be shifted towards a platformer (by careful placement of platforms) or a puzzle game (by extensive use of buttons, keys, and doors).
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Some FPS maps may be designed to prevent sniping by not including any long hallways, while other maps may allow for a mix of sniping and closer combat.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] A *minigame* (also spelled mini-game or mini game, sometimes called a subgame or microgame) is a short video game often contained within another video game, and sometimes in application software or on a display of any form of hardware.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] A minigame contains different gameplay elements than the main game, may be optional, and is often smaller or more simplistic than the game in which it is contained.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Minigames are sometimes also offered separately for free to promote the main game.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Some minigames can also be bonus stages or secret levels.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] They are distinguishable from levels in that a level is an environment bound to a set of mechanics and rules that all defines all other normal levels in a game, whereas a minigame can use different rules and playstyles but may not necessarily be set in a different environment.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Level designers sometimes make hidden rooms and areas that usually require more effort for the player to reach or to notice.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] These usually give some additional rewards, such as ammo or powerups.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] They serve to induce players to explore.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Sometimes, they serve as easter eggs, containing messages such as the level designers' names or pictures, or political or humorous messages.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] One of the first games with a 3D engine to feature hidden features was *Wolfenstein 3D*, where certain walls could be pushed to reveal hidden passages.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Sometimes, a whole level may be designed as a secret level.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] A bonus stage (also known as a bonus level, special stage or bonus round) is a special level within a video game designed to reward the player or players, and typically allows the player to collect extra points or power-ups.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Bonus stage either have no enemies or hazards, or replace the normal penalties for being struck by enemies or hazards with simply being thrown out of the bonus stage.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Many bonus stages need to be activated or discovered in some manner, or certain conditions must be satisfied to access them.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Otherwise, they appear after the player has completed a certain number of regular stages.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] There are many map bugs that level designers try to avoid, but sometimes go unnoticed for some time.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] A player might get stuck in map geometry with no way to escape or to die.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] A player might be able to find a specific spot where they do not have to move to gain experience, because monsters are constantly spawned but can be easily and immediately killed.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] In multiplayer maps, a player may be able to reach areas of the map designed to be inaccessible; for example, reaching an advantageous rooftop position and camping other players.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] A player might be able to fall out-of-bounds of a map where other players cannot reach them.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Invisible walls are cited to be level design bugs, and might be "left-over geometry" from an earlier version of the level or an object's improperly aligned "collision box".
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] In some cases, specific mapping tools can be designed to automatically detect problems such as falling "outside" a level, and reaching "stuck" areas.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] Careful level designers run these tools as the last step before releasing a new version of a level.
[src:level-editor-design/level-design] In most cases, the best way to improve a map is by playtesting it with experienced players, and allowing them to try to exploit any problems.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] Official level editors are typically made to assist game development or to allow for greater player creativity, while fan-made editors are usually created for easier modding.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] Level editors vary in complexity; editors used in game development are usually more difficult and extensive than those made with players in mind.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] Modern level editors often allow to upload created levels online and play other uploaded user-made levels.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] Level editors often have a substantial effect on the game's longevity.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] In 2008, *LittleBigPlanet* was released, featuring a robust level editor and an ability to share levels online.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] Unlike other games with a level editor, where it was featured as a side mode, the editor in *LittleBigPlanet* was the main selling point.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] The game was universally acclaimed for its amount of content and the unique approach to user-generated content.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] Later games in the *LittleBigPlanet* series expanded the formula, adding more features to the editor.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] Since the late 2000s, an increasing number of games with a level editor also featured a way to share them online via in-game services or external dedicated websites, like Steam Workshop.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] On these services, users are able to download other people's levels and, in some cases, rate them based on their perceived quality.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] In 2015, Nintendo released *Super Mario Maker*, another game with a level editor as the main focus of the game.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] The editor was designed to be accessible and easy to understand.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] Users could upload their levels online and play other people's levels, as well as vote for (like) or against (boo) them.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] The level editor was praised for being intuitive and easy to understand, while still allowing to create unique levels.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] Later games with level editors are often influenced by and compared to *Super Mario Maker*.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] In 2019, Nintendo released *Super Mario Maker 2*, a sequel to the first game with even more features.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] The developer of a video game may include built-in level editing tools; for example, a track editor for a racing game, or release an official level editor for the game as a separate application.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] In cases where the game doesn't have an official level editor, players of the game develop fan-made editors, such as Lunar Magic for *Super Mario World*.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] Level editors are present extensively in video game integrated development environments, such as Godot, Unity, or Unreal Engine.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] Most in-game level editors impose object limits to prevent performance issues, crashes, and exploits.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] This is especially prevalent in editors available on game consoles, such as *Halo*'s Forge.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] top-down map editor is a simple to understand grid-based editor.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] level editor is significantly more complex, but gives user more options.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] The complexity of a game's level editor and the number of available options given to the player are usually proportional.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] While in most games level editors are an additional feature, certain games have the level editor as the main feature of the game, such as *Super Mario Maker* and *LittleBigPlanet*.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] Some games, like *Dreams* and *Game Builder Garage*, allow users to make their own assets and develop custom logic, effectively functioning as game creation systems.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] Most modern games with level editors allow creators to upload their levels online, which are then able to be played by other people.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] To upload a level, there is usually a requirement to beat the level beforehand, preventing impossible levels to be uploaded.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] Level editors are most often present in two-dimensional tile-based video games, typically featuring a square grid on which level elements are placed.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] These editors often provide drag-and-drop functionality along with tools for moving, deleting, and adjusting properties of objects.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] Similar to various graphics software, layering may also be used to separate overlapping objects.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] Three-dimensional level editors are usually reserved for game development; user-friendly 3D editors are far less common, because of the increased complexity required to build in three dimensions, as well as to program such level editor.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] 3D editors typically have a virtual camera that can be moved freely to view the level.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] Early 3D editors sometimes displayed orthographic projections of the level on each axis; this was used to precisely place brushes.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] The presence of a level editor in a video game can often increase its longevity and prolong the game's popularity.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] Various news sources report that *Portal 2* continued to receive new community maps made in the game's chamber editor even after 13 years since the game's release in 2011.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] Released in 2013, *Geometry Dash* was a modest success at launch, but the game's community has been steadily growing since then, partly because of the online levels created by players.
[src:level-editor-design/level-editor] *Super Mario Maker 2* has received over two million levels in the first eleven days after the game's release; this has then increased to 26 million by 3 May 2021.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] A video game with **nonlinear gameplay** presents players with challenges that can be completed in a number of different sequences.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Each may take on (or even encounter) only some of the challenges possible, and the same challenges may be played in a different order.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Conversely, a video game with **linear gameplay** will confront a player with a fixed sequence of challenges: every player faces every challenge and has to overcome them in the same order.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] A nonlinear game will allow greater player freedom than a linear game.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] For example, a nonlinear game may permit multiple sequences to finish the game, a choice between paths to victory, different types of victory, or optional side-quests and subplots.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Some games feature both linear and nonlinear elements, and some games offer a sandbox mode that allows players to explore an open world game environment independently from the game's main objectives, if any objectives are provided at all.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] A game that is significantly nonlinear is sometimes described as being open-ended or a sandbox, and is characterized by allowing players to measure progress through self-determined goals, independent of scripted game elements.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] A game level or world can be linear, nonlinear or both.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] In a linear game, there is only one path the player can take through a level, but in games with nonlinear gameplay, players might have to revisit locations or choose from multiple paths to finish the level.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] As with other game elements, linear level design is not absolute.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] While a nonlinear level can give the freedom to explore or backtrack, there can be a sequence of challenges that a player must solve to complete the level.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] If a player must confront the challenges in a fixed order nonlinear games will often give multiple approaches to achieve said objectives.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] A more linear game requires a player to finish levels in a fixed sequence to win.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] The ability to skip, repeat, or choose between levels makes this type of game less linear.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] *Super Mario Bros.* is an early example of this, where the player had access to warp zones that skipped many levels of the game.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] In some games, levels can change between linear design and free roaming depending on the objective of the stage.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] *Super Mario 64* is an example where the main stages are free roam, while the levels where Bowser is encountered follow a straight path to the end.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] When a game is sufficiently large and open-ended, it may be described as an open world or as a sandbox game.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Open-world game designs have existed in some form since the 1980s, such as the space trading game *Elite*, and often make use of procedurally generated environments.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] In a game with a sandbox mode, a player may turn off or ignore game objectives, or have unlimited access to items.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] This can open up possibilities that were not intended by the game designer.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] A sandbox mode is an option in otherwise goal-oriented games and is distinguished from open-ended games that have no objectives, such as *SimCity*, and *Garry's Mod*.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Games that employ linear stories are those where the player cannot change the story line or ending of the story.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Many games have offered premature endings should the player fail to meet an objective, but these are usually just interruptions in a player's progress rather than actual endings.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Even in games with a linear story, players interact with the game world by performing a variety of actions along the way.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] More recently, some games have begun offering multiple endings to increase the dramatic effect of moral choices within the game, although early examples also exist.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Still, some games have gone beyond small choices or special endings, offering a branching storyline (also known as an interactive narrative outside of a video game context), that players may control at critical points in the game.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Sometimes the player is given a choice of which branch of the plot to follow, while sometimes the path will be based on the player's success or failure at a specific challenge.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] For example, Black Isle Studios' *Fallout* series of role-playing video games features numerous quests where player actions dictate the outcome of the story behind the objectives.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Players can eliminate in-game characters permanently from the virtual world should they choose to do so, and by doing so may actually alter the number and type of quests that become available to them as the game progresses.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] The effects of such decisions may not be immediate.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Branches of the story may merge or split at different points in the game, but seldom allow backtracking.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Some games even allow for different starting points, and one way this is done is through a character selection screen.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Linear stories cost less time and money to develop, since there is only one fixed sequence of events and no major decisions to keep track of.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] For example, several games from the *Wing Commander* series offered a branching storyline, but eventually they were abandoned as too expensive.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Nonlinear stories increase the chances for bugs or absurdities if they are not tested properly, although they do provide greater player freedom.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Some players have also responded negatively to branching stories because it is hard and tedious for them to experience the "full value" of all the game's content.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] As a compromise between linear and branching stories, there are also games where stories split into branches and then fold back into a single storyline.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] In these stories, the plot will branch, but then converge upon some inevitable event, giving the impression of a nonlinear gameplay through the use of nonlinear narrative, without the use of interactive narratives.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] This is typically used in many graphic adventure games.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] A truly nonlinear story would be written entirely by the actions of the player, and thus remains a difficult design challenge.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] As such, there is often little or no story in video games with a truly nonlinear gameplay.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Branching storylines are a common trend in visual novels, a subgenre of interactive narrative and adventure games.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Visual novels frequently use multiple branching storylines to achieve multiple different endings, allowing nonlinear freedom of choice along the way.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Decision points within a visual novel often present players with the option of altering the course of events during the game, leading to many different possible outcomes.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Visual novels are popular in East Asia, especially in Japan where they account for nearly 70% of personal computer games released there.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] An acclaimed example is *999: Nine Hours, Nine Persons, Nine Doors*, where nearly every action and dialogue choice can lead to entirely new branching paths and endings.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Each path only reveals certain aspects of the overall storyline and it is only after uncovering all the possible different paths and outcomes through multiple playthroughs that everything comes together to form a coherent well-written story.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] It is not uncommon for visual novels to have morality systems.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] *School Days* instead encourages players to explore the grey, neutral middle-ground in order to view more interesting, "bad" endings.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] It is also not uncommon for visual novels to have multiple protagonists giving different perspectives on the story.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] C's Ware's *EVE Burst Error* (1995) introduced a unique twist to the system by allowing the player to switch between both protagonists at any time during the game, instead of finishing one protagonist's scenario before playing the other.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] *EVE Burst Error* often requires the player to have both protagonists co-operate with each other at various points during the game, with choices in one scenario affecting the other.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] *Fate/stay night* is another example that features multiple perspectives.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Chunsoft sound novels such as *Machi* (1998) and *428: Shibuya Scramble* (2008) develop this concept further, by allowing the player to alternate between the perspectives of several or more different characters, making choices with one character that have consequences for other characters.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] *428* in particular features up to 85 different possible endings.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Another approach to nonlinear storytelling can be seen in *Cosmology of Kyoto*.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] The game lacks an overall plot, but it instead presents fragmented narratives and situations in a nonlinear manner, as the player character encounters various non-player characters while wandering the city.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] These narratives are cross-referenced to an encyclopedia, providing background information as the narratives progress and as the player comes across various characters and locations, with various stories, situations and related information appearing at distinct locations.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] It provides enough freedom to allow for the player to experiment with the game, such as using it as a resource for their own role-playing game campaign, for example.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Branching storylines are also often used in role-playing video games (RPGs) to an extent.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] An early example, published in 1999, is the fantasy role-playing game *Might and Magic VII: For Blood and Honor*, where players have to choose between Light and Dark.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] While the dark side wants to destroy the world of Enroth, the light side tries to save it.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] The choice determines which grandmaster levels the player characters can obtain and the quests they have to do in that part of the game.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Earlier in the game, the player already has to choose sides in a border conflict between Elves and Humans, or remain neutral.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] This affects the flag in their Castle Harmondale and a few quests, but not the outcome.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] A second example is Obsidian Entertainment's *Fallout: New Vegas*, where the player's decisions influence whether one of three different factions gain control of the area surrounding post-apocalyptic Las Vegas.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] These factions include Caesar's Legion, a group of Roman-esque slavers; the New California Republic (NCR), an expansionist military government; and Mr.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] House, the enigmatic *de facto* ruler of New Vegas, in command of an army of robots that patrols the city.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Each of the three sides aim to control Hoover Dam, which is still operational and supplying the American Southwest with power and clean, non-irradiated water; thus, control of the dam means effective control of the region.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] A fourth option, siding with a robot named Yes Man and prevailing upon or eliminating the other faction leaders, enables the player to go solo and take over the Hoover Dam for themselves.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Another RPG example is tri-Ace's *Star Ocean* series, where the storyline is not affected by moral alignments like in other role-playing games, but inspired by dating sims, by friendship and relationship points between each of the characters.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] *Star Ocean: The Second Story* in particular offers as many as 86 different endings with hundreds of permutations, setting a benchmark for the number of possible outcomes of a video game.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Later games in the series added several variations, including an action gauge that can be raised up or down depending on the situation, and a gauge that the player can manipulate using the analog stick depending on the situation.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] A similar type of conversation system later appeared in a more recent action role-playing game also published by Sega, *Alpha Protocol*.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Another unique take on the concept is combining nonlinear branching storytelling with the concepts of time travel and parallel universes.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] Early attempts at such an approach included Squaresoft's *Chrono* role-playing game series (1995–1999) and ELF's visual novel *YU-NO: A girl who chants love at the bound of this world* (1996).
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] *Radiant Historia* takes it further by giving players the freedom to travel backwards and forwards through a timeline to alter the course of history, with each of their choices and actions significantly affect the timeline.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] The player can return to certain points in history and live through certain events again to make different choices and see different possible outcomes on the timeline.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] The player can also travel back and forth between two parallel timelines, and can obtain many possible parallel endings.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] The PSP version of *Tactics Ogre* featured a "World" system that allows players to revisit key plot points and make different choices to see how the story unfolds differently.
[src:level-editor-design/nonlinear-gameplay] *Final Fantasy XIII-2* also features a similar nonlinear time travel system to *Radiant Historia*.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] The **video game designer** is like the director of a film; the designer is the visionary of the game and controls the artistic and technical elements of the game in fulfillment of their vision.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] However, with complex games, such as MMORPGs or a big budget action or sports title, designers may number in the dozens.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] In these cases, there are generally one or two principal designers and multiple junior designers who specify subsets or subsystems of the game.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] As the industry has aged and embraced alternative production methodologies such as agile, the role of a principal game designer has begun to separate - some studios emphasizing the auteur model while others emphasizing a more team oriented model.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] In larger companies like Electronic Arts, each aspect of the game (control, level design) may have a separate producer, lead designer and several general designers.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Video game design requires artistic and technical competence as well as sometimes including writing skills.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Historically, video game programmers have sometimes comprised the entire design team.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] This is the case of such noted designers as Sid Meier, John Romero, Chris Sawyer and Will Wright.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] A notable exception to this policy was Coleco, which from its very start separated the function of design and programming.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] As video games became more complex, computers and consoles became more powerful, the job of the game designer became separate from the lead programmer.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Soon, game complexity demanded team members focused on game design.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] A number of early veterans chose the game design path eschewing programming and delegating those tasks to others.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Video game design starts with an idea, often a variation or modification on an existing concept.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] The game idea will fall within one or several genres and designers will often experiment with mixing genres.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] The game designer usually produces an initial game proposal document containing the concept, gameplay, feature list, setting and story, target audience, requirements and schedule, staff and budget estimates.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Multiple design decisions are made during the course of a game's development; it is the responsibility of the designer to decide which elements should be implemented.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] For example, consistency with the game's vision, budget or hardware limitations.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Design changes will have a significant impact on required resources.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] The designer may use scripting languages to implement and preview design ideas without necessarily modifying the game's codebase.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] A game designer often plays video games and demos to follow the markets' development.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Over time, it has become common for a game designer's name to misleadingly be given an undue amount of association to the game, neglecting the rest of the development team.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] This is in stark contrast to the industries' origins, when creators were often given little to no recognition.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Coincidentally, this lack of credit lead Warren Robinett to create the first Easter egg in a video game.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Funding, traditionally provided by game publishers, who may have specific expectations from a game, must be taken into account, as most video games are *market-driven* — developed to sell for profit.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] However, if financial issues do not influence designer's decisions, the game can become *design-* or *designer-driven*; but few games are designed this way, with it becoming more common among indie game developers, alongside alternative sources of funding, like Early Access or Crowdfunding.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Alternatively, a game may be *technology-driven*, such as Quake (1996), to show off a particular hardware achievement or to market the game engine.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Finally, a game may be *art-driven*, such as *Myst* (1993) and Journey (2012), mainly to show off impressive visuals designed by artists.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] A game designer is a person who designs gameplay, conceiving and designing the rules and structure of a game.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Multiple designers start their career in testing departments, other roles in game development or in classroom conditions, where mistakes by others can be seen first-hand.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] In 2010, a game designer with more than six years of experience earned an average of US$65,000 (£44,761.22 sterling), US$54,000 (£37,186.24) with three to six years of experience and $44,000 (£30,299.90) with less than 3 years of experience.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Lead designers earned $75,000 (£51,647.56) with three to six years of experience and $95,000 (£65,420.24) with more than six years of experience.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] In 2013, a game designer with less than 3 years of experience earned, on average, $55,000 (£37,874.88).
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] A game designer with more than 6 years of experience made, on average, $105,000 (£72,306.58).
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] The average salary of these designers varies depending on their region.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] As of 2015 the salary of experienced workers has shifted to approximately US$87,000 (£59,911.17) As of January 17, 2020, the average annual pay for a game designer in the United States is $130,000 a year.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] World design is the creation of a backstory, setting and theme for the game; often done by a lead designer.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] World design can also be the creation of a universe or a map, as well as topics or areas that are likely to be pursued by the player.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] It is a map referenced for creation of everything as it shows where it is and allows for the most logistical design in any given game.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] World design shapes the direction the game goes towards.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] System design is the creation of game rules and underlying mathematical patterns.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] System design is the enacted simulation of a game designed to interact or react with the player.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] The "experience" a player has with a game is attributed to how the game's system is designed.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] A complex system with depth leads to a more unpredictable strand of events to immerse the player into the video game.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Content design is the creation of characters, items, puzzles, missions, or any aspect of the game that is not required for it to function properly and meet the minimum viable product standard.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] In essence, content is the complexity added to a minimum viable product to increase its value.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Game writing involves writing dialogue, text and story.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] This is one of the first steps that go into making a video game.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] This encompasses a number of different elements of the process.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Writing in video games also includes the elements in which the literature is presented.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Voice acting, text, picture editing and music are all elements of game writing.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Level design is the construction of world levels and its features.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Level design makes use of a range of different fields to create a game world.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Lighting, space, framing, color and contrast are used to draw a player's attention.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] A designer can then use these elements to guide or direct the player in a specific direction through the game world or mislead them.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] User interface (UI) design deals with the construction the user interactions and feedback interface, like menus or heads-up displays.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] The user interface also incorporates game mechanics design.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Deciding how much information to give the player and in what way allows the designer to inform the player about the world, or perhaps leave them uninformed.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Another aspect to consider is the method of input a game will use and deciding to what degree a player can interact with a game with these inputs.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] These choices have a profound effect on the mood of the game, as it directly affects the player in both noticeable and subtle ways.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] User interface design in video games has unique goals.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] A conscious decision has to be made regarding the amount of information to relay to the player.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] However, the UI in games do not have to be absolutely streamlined.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Players expect challenges and are willing to accept them as long as the experience is sufficiently rewarding.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] By the same token, navigating or interaction with a game's UI can be satisfying without the need to be effortless.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Audio design involves the process of creating or incorporating all of the sounds that are in the game, like music, sound effects or voice acting.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] This includes the theme song and jingles used in title screens and menus.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] The disciplines listed above all combine to form the discipline of game feel.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] It ensures that the flow of the game and the user interaction with the game elements are functioning smoothly.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Numerous games have narrative elements which give a context to an event in a game, making the activity of playing it less abstract and enhance its entertainment value, although narrative elements are not always clearly present or present at all.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] The original version of *Tetris* is an example of a game apparently without narrative.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Some narratologists claim that all games have a narrative element.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Some go further and claim that games are essentially a form of narrative.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Narrative in practice can be the starting point for the development of a game or can be added to a design that started as a set of game mechanics.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Gameplay is the interactive aspects of video game design.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Gameplay involves player interaction with the game, usually for the purpose of gameplay is entertainment, education or training.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] The design process varies from designer to designer and companies have different formal procedures and philosophies.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] The typical "textbook" approach is to start with a concept or a previously completed game and from there create a game design document.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] This document is intended to map out the complete game design and acts as a central resource for the development team.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] This document should ideally be updated as the game evolves throughout the production process.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Designers are frequently expected to adapt to multiple roles of widely varying nature; for example, concept prototyping can be assisted with the use of pre-existing engines and tools like GameMaker Studio, Unity, Godot or Construct.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Level designs might be done first on paper and again for the game engine using a 3D modeling tool.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Scripting languages are used for multiple elements—AI, cutscenes, GUI, environmental processes, and a number of other behaviors and effects—that designers would want to tune without a programmer's assistance.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Setting, story and character concepts require a research and writing process.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Designers may oversee focus testing, write up art and audio asset lists and write game documentation.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] In addition to the skillset, designers are ideally clear communicators with attention to detail and ability to delegate responsibilities appropriately.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Design approval in the commercial setting is a continuous process from the earliest stages until the game ships.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] When a new project is being discussed (either internally or as a result of dialogue with potential publishers), the designer may be asked to write a sell-sheet of short concepts, followed by a one or two-page pitch of specific features, audience, platform and other details.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Designers will first meet with leads in other departments to establish agreement on the feasibility of the game given the available time, scope and budget.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] If the pitch is approved, early milestones focus on the creation of a fleshed-out design document.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Some developers advocate a prototyping phase before the design document is written to experiment with new ideas before they become part of the design.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] As production progresses, designers are asked to make frequent decisions about elements missing from the design.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] The consequences of these decisions are hard to predict and often can only be determined after creating the full implementation.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] These are referred to as the *unknowns* of the design and the faster they are uncovered, the less risk the team faces later in the production process.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Outside factors such as budget cuts or changes in milestone expectations also result in cuts to the design and while overly large cuts can take the heart out of a project, cuts can also result in a streamlined design with only the essential features, polished well.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Towards the end of production, designers take the brunt of responsibility for ensuring that the gameplay remains at a uniform standard throughout the game, even in very long games.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] This task is made more difficult under "crunch" conditions, as the entire team may begin to lose sight of the core gameplay once pressured to hit a date for a finished and bug-free game.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Traditionally, game designers used simple tools like Word, Excel or just plain pen and paper.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] As the field has evolved and player agency and localization started to play a bigger role in game development, the need for professional tools has emerged for this particular field.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Examples of software for narrative design and storytelling include articy:draft 3 and Twine.
[src:level-editor-design/video-game-design] Tools like these often help to inform the earliest stages of the design and development process, before visual content and software development is started in earnest.
